{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14731"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14731"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.26,0.17,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111791"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111791"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her blood pressure. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include metformin and amlodipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 76/min, blood pressure 148/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Recent investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine protein/creatinine ratio 150 mg/mmol (\u0026lt; 30) \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 45 mL/min/1.73kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt; 90). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate systolic blood pressure target?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Less than 120-130 mmHg","Less than 135 mmHg","Less than 140-150 mmHg","Less than 145 mmHg","Less than 160 mmHg"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has significant proteinuria (protein/creatinine ratio 150 mg/mmol) and chronic kidney disease. The presence of proteinuria is a marker of kidney damage and a risk factor for progression of kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. However in patients at high of cardiovascular risk - such as those with previous myocardial infarction or stroke, diabetes with microalbuminuria (as in this case), moderate to severe CKD (also seen in this case) or familial hypercholesterolaemia - more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;120 mmHg) \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate. However, such targets require careful monitoring for treatment-related adverse effects, including hypotension, syncope, electrolyte disturbances, and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent RACGP guidelines for management of type II diabetes recommend aiming for an intermediate systolic blood pressure target of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;130 mmHg \u003C/strong\u003Ein patients with diabetes and chronic kidney disease. This aims to balance the cardiovascular risk reduction benefits of strict blood pressure control while minimising adverse effect risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore aiming for blood pressures \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;120-130 mmHg \u003C/strong\u003Ewith shared decision making and consideration of adverse effects is reasonable in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe preferred agents for achieving this target would be ACE inhibitors or ARBs, as they have specific renoprotective effects beyond blood pressure lowering through reduction of intraglomerular pressure and proteinuria. Regular monitoring of serum creatinine and potassium is essential when initiating these medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood pressure targets in proteinuric chronic kidney disease should be less than 120/90 mmHg to slow disease progression, with careful monitoring for treatment related adverse events.","ACE inhibitors and ARBs are first-line agents for proteinuric kidney disease due to their renoprotective effects.","Regular monitoring of serum creatinine and potassium is essential when initiating ACE inhibitors or ARBs."],"references":["National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance. Australian Absolute Cardiovascular Disease Risk Calculator[Internet]. Melbourne: NVDPA; [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Morris S, Manickavasagam V. Advanced chronic kidney disease: Considerations for renin-angiotensin system inhibitor use as disease processes. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2023;52:209-13. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2023/april/advanced-chronic-kidney-disease","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Management of type 2 diabetes: a handbook for general practice. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP; 2020. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/7fe75f75-56e0-40e6-a433-12bd15537c5a/Management-of-type-2-diabetes-A-handbook-for-general-practice.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93861"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93861"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T21:36:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T21:36:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111791"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"update